00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:06,980
In this video we are going to do step four, which is Entity Framework core SQL server connection string

2
00:00:06,980 --> 00:00:09,410
in the Application settings Json file.

3
00:00:09,830 --> 00:00:16,160
In ordering microservices, we will use SQL server database as a backing services, and we will also

4
00:00:16,160 --> 00:00:18,890
add SQL server into our Docker compose file.

5
00:00:18,890 --> 00:00:22,580
But now let's focus on the development part of the Entity Framework core.

6
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:28,010
For that purpose, please open the Visual Studio and go to the Application Settings.

7
00:00:28,010 --> 00:00:33,020
In ordering API, we will have application settings in the web project.

8
00:00:33,020 --> 00:00:38,240
If you open the ordering API project, you can go to the Application Settings Json file.

9
00:00:38,240 --> 00:00:41,480
And I'm going to define connection settings in here.

10
00:00:41,480 --> 00:00:48,500
As you know that application settings is typically in ASP.Net core project and storing application settings

11
00:00:48,500 --> 00:00:50,630
like database connection strings.

12
00:00:50,630 --> 00:00:54,020
And I'm going to put connection strings in this file.

13
00:00:54,020 --> 00:00:59,480
And if you look at this connection string you can see that we have connection string database.

14
00:00:59,480 --> 00:01:04,430
And as a server I am giving a localhost which is specifies the database server.

15
00:01:04,430 --> 00:01:09,200
Localhost means the database is running on the same machine as the web application.

16
00:01:09,200 --> 00:01:14,750
When we are containerize this application, we will change the server name as a Docker container name,

17
00:01:14,750 --> 00:01:18,590
and after that you can see the database name as a order db.

18
00:01:18,620 --> 00:01:22,010
This is the name of the database to connect to SQL server.

19
00:01:22,010 --> 00:01:24,230
In this case we will give order db.

20
00:01:24,230 --> 00:01:27,080
And here you can see the user id sa.

21
00:01:27,080 --> 00:01:33,020
And this is the username for SQL server login SA stands for the System administrator.

22
00:01:33,020 --> 00:01:36,020
For password I'm giving a complex password.

23
00:01:36,020 --> 00:01:38,120
This is for the SQL server login.

24
00:01:38,120 --> 00:01:43,940
And if you continue the connection string you can see the encrypt as a false.

25
00:01:43,940 --> 00:01:49,850
This indicates whether the connection should be encrypted or not for development environments.

26
00:01:49,850 --> 00:01:55,940
Mostly it is using as a false because we don't need the encryption in development environment, and

27
00:01:55,940 --> 00:02:01,130
after that we have trusted server certificate configuration as a true.

28
00:02:01,160 --> 00:02:07,790
This is often used in development environment where the SSL TLS certificate might not be certificate

29
00:02:07,790 --> 00:02:08,870
or SQL server.

30
00:02:08,870 --> 00:02:09,710
So that's why.

31
00:02:09,710 --> 00:02:12,920
Please give true for the trust server certificate.

32
00:02:12,920 --> 00:02:18,830
And this is the connection settings for communicating SQL server from our ordering API project.

